es a case for localising the UNEPS proposal and the author suggests that UNEPS' architects might consider developing a less ambitious proposal as a first step to creating a rapidly deployable service with the mandate to prevent atrocity crimes. It examines various alternatives towards this end and concludes that, because the UNEPS proposal is intricately linked to the UN, trust in the world organisation is an essential ingredient in generating support for the idea. It argues that a central way of achieving this is to ensure that the values and priorities of a wide range of stakeholders are seen to be represented in the organisation's structure and workings"--cProvided by publisher.  a16 4320aUnited Nations.bEmergency Peace Service.20aUnited NationsxPeacekeeping forces. 0aResponsibility to protect (International law) 0aAtrocitiesxPrevention. 0aGlobal politics and the responsibility to protect.  aJZ 6374 H47 2015hUAAU-Bi0162035240587  aJZ 6374 H47 2015wLCc1i0162035240587lON_SHELFmUAAUGp$150.00rYsYtBOOKu2/19/2015  aJZ 6374 H47 2015wLCc1i0162035253408d4/10/2015e4/10/2015lON_SHELFmUAHSSn2p$150.00rYsYtBOOKu3/11/201501ahttp://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n79021345